<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

 <subsection xml:id="subsec-length-of-an-arc-of-a-circle-2">
    <title>Length of an arc of a circle 2</title>
    <p>
      
    </p>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <sidebyside>
        <p>
          <ul>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>\textbf{Materials Needed:}</m> Paper plates or circular paper cutouts (one per group), Rulers, Protractors, Scissors, Colored pencils or markers and Calculator (optional)
              </p>
              <p>
                <ol>
                  <li>
                    <p>
                       Imagine you have a slice of pizza that’s a part of a big circular pizza. If you were to walk all the way around that slice (along the crust and down both sides), how far would you walk?"
                    </p>
                  </li>
                </ol>
              </p>
            </li>
          </ul>
        </p>
        <image source="/pizza-grade-eight.png">
          <shortdescription>pizza image</shortdescription>
         </image>
      </sidebyside>
      <p>
        2, Creating a Sector
      </p>
      <p>
        (a) Take a paper circle.
      </p>
      <p>
        (b) Mark the center and draw a radius.
      </p>
      <p>
       (c)  Using a protractor, measure and draw a central angle (e.g. 90°, 120°, or 60°).
      </p>
      <p>
        (d) Cut out the sector (like a pizza slice).
      </p>
      <p>
        3. Measuring the Arc Length
      </p>
      <p>
        (a) Use a ruler to Measure the length of the radius (r).
      </p>
      <p>
        (b) Use a protractor to measure the angle of the sector (θ)
      </p>
      <p>
        (c) Use string or a flexible ruler to trace and measure the arc (for estimation).
      </p>
      <p>
      (d) Use the formula for arc length to calculate the length of the arc.
      </p>
      <p>
        4. Calculating the Arc Length
      <md>
        <mrow> \text{Arc Length} = \amp \frac{\theta}{360^\circ} \times 2 \pi r</mrow>
      </md>
      </p>
      
      </statement>
    </activity>
    <example>
      <statement>
        <p>
          What is the length of the arc of a circle with a radius of 9 cm and a central angle of 135° as shown below?
        </p>
        <image>
          <latex-image>
            \begin{tikzpicture}
            % Draw sector
            \filldraw[fill=yellow!60, draw=black] 
              (0,0) -- (9,0) 
              arc[start angle=0, end angle=135, radius=9] -- cycle;
          
            % Draw radius label
            \draw[&lt;-] (4.5,0) -- +(0,-0.8) node[below] {9 cm};
          
            % Draw angle arc and label
            \draw (1.5,0) arc[start angle=0, end angle=135, radius=1.5];
            \node at (1.2,1) {135°};
            \end{tikzpicture}
          </latex-image>
        </image>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <statement>
          <p>
            To find the length of the arc, we can use the formula:
            <md>
              <mrow> \text{Arc Length} = \amp \frac{\theta}{360^\circ} \times 2 \pi r</mrow>
              <mrow> \text{Arc Length} = \amp \frac{135^\circ}{360^\circ} \times 2 \pi (9) </mrow>
              <mrow> \text{Arc Length} = \amp \frac{135}{360} \times 18 \pi </mrow>
              <mrow> \text{Arc Length} = \amp \frac{3}{8} \times 18 \pi </mrow>
              <mrow> \text{Arc Length} = \amp \frac{54 \pi}{8} </mrow>
              <mrow> \text{Arc Length} = \amp 6.75 \times 3.14</mrow>
              <mrow> \text{Arc Length} = \amp 21.21 \text{ cm}</mrow>
            </md>
          <p>
            Therefore, the length of the arc is approximately 21.21 cm.
          </p>  
          </p>
        </statement>
      </solution>
    </example>  
    
    
  </subsection>